{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6aa286f4-2d3d-4e4e-aaac-630574d65ab3","content":"TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively, so you filter with `--treenode-filter` instead of `--filter`. The command is:\n\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nThis matches the `SmsNotificationTests` class anywhere in the test tree and runs both `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"64832fe6-6ee4-443c-9124-2bf863a06496","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project (v0.6.120). TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) by default. For MTP-based runners, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nFor TUnit on MTP, you use `--treenode-filter` to filter tests. To filter by class name:\n\n```\ndotnet run --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. TUnit uses MTP natively. The way to run TUnit tests:\n\n- TUnit projects have `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`, so they compile to an executable.\n\n\n- You can invoke them with either `dotnet run` or `dotnet test` depending on how the project is configured.\n- With MTP, the filtering uses `--treenode-filter` syntax to target specific test classes.\n\nThe treenode hierarchy follows the pattern `/Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test`, so to filter all tests in `SmsNotificationTests`, I can use either the specific path `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` or the broader wildcard pattern `/**/SmsNotificationTests/**`. The broader pattern is more robust and should work reliably.\n\nFor TUnit specifically, I need to consider whether `dotnet test` properly passes through the `--treenode-filter` argument, or if `dotnet run` is the more reliable approach depending on the TUnit version. Both commands should work with the filter syntax, though the exact invocation might vary slightly between versions.","outputTokens":912,"requestId":"A02C:2D289A:DA28B1:FF5576:69FE8EE0"},"id":"691